1. Implement a vector function¶

In [98]:
#A as a unit matrix
A = [[1,0],[0,1]]
x = np.arange(1,3).reshape(2,1)


#Vector Function
def vectorX(x):
    #xMatTranspose = xMat.transpose()
    y = x.T @ A @ x
    return y

vectorX(x)
Out[98]:
array([[5]])

2. Implement its gradient¶

In [100]:
#Gradient function
def gradX(x):
    gradientX = 2 * A @ x
    return gradientX

gradX(x)
Out[100]:
array([[1],
       [2],
       [1],
       [2]])

3. Visualize the function¶

In [86]:
# compute and plot the function
# we do it with loop so it is easier to be used in GD algorithm
def plot_graph(x):
    x1range = [-5,5]
    x2range = [-5,5]

    ex1 = np.linspace(x1range[0], x1range[1], 30)
    ex2 = np.linspace(x2range[0], x2range[1], 30)
    (xm1, xm2) = np.meshgrid(ex1, ex2)
    x1 = xm1.ravel()
    x2 = xm2.ravel()
    z = np.empty_like(xm1)
    g1 = np.empty_like(xm1)
    g2 = np.empty_like(xm1)
    for i in range(30):
        for j in range(30):
            x = np.array((xm1[i,j], xm2[i,j]))
            z[i,j] = vectorX(x)
            g = gradX(x)
            g1[i,j] = g[0]
            g2[i,j] = g[1]

    fig = plt.figure(figsize = [10,10])
    ax = fig.add_subplot(111)
    ax.set_aspect('equal')
    # ensure equal aspect ratio
    cs = ax.contour(ex1, ex2, z)
    # make contour plot
    ax.clabel(cs, inline=1)
    # add contour values
    ax.quiver(ex1, ex2, g1, g2)
    # add arrows for the other function ff

A = [[1,0],[0,1]]

3.3 Does gradient point to the steepest climb of the function values?
Yes the gradient point to the steepest climb. When we fold the above graph through its center, all the arrows points upwards

4. Play with parameters¶

4.1. A is positive definite (All eigen values are positive)¶

In [102]:
A = [[15, 15], [10,10]]
print(np.linalg.eig(A)[0])
plot_graph(x)

[ 25.   0.]

For a matrix which has all eigen values as positive, all the arrows in the graph points upwards towards the highest point.

4.2. A is negative definite (All eigen values are negative)¶

In [136]:
A = [[-2, -1], [-3, -5]]
print(np.linalg.eig(A)[0])
plot_graph(x)

[-1.20871215 -5.79128785]
5.38575353189

For a matrix which has all negative eigen values, all the arrows in the graph points downwards towards the lowest point.

4.3. A is indefinite (it has both positive and negative eigenvalues)¶

In [105]:
A = np.arange(1,5).reshape(2,2)
print(np.linalg.eig(A)[0])
plot_graph(x)

[-0.37228132  5.37228132]

For a matrix that is indefinite with both positive and negative eigen values, all the arrows in the graph points upwards towards the highest point.

4.4. A is a diagonal matrix¶

In [135]:
A = [[20, 0], [0, -45]]
print(np.linalg.eig(A)[0])
plot_graph(x)

[ 20. -45.]
2.25

For a diagonal matrix, the arrows points downwards and then converge towards the sides.

4.5. A is not a diagonal matrix¶

In [114]:
A = [[20, 10], [0, -25]]
print(np.linalg.eig(A)[0])
plot_graph(x)

[ 20. -25.]

For a non-diagnol matrix, the arrows converges around the corner. The arrows points sidewards towards the mid.

4.6. A has small condition number (say, k < 2)¶

In [130]:
A = [[20, 10], [0, -20]]
print(np.linalg.eig(A)[0])
print("The condition number is ", np.linalg.cond(A))
plot_graph(x)

[ 20. -20.]
The condition number is  1.6403882032

For a matrix with condition number less than 2, the graph has arrows that points both upwards and downwards around the corners
